  "author_association": "MEMBER",
  "body": "I set up a 3 node k8s 1.7.5 cluster, modified `cluster/examples/kubernetes/rook-cluster.yaml` to set \"hostNetwork: true\", then brought up rook and the wordpress example, along with rook-tools.  When I attempted to use rook-tools, the `$ROOK_API_SERVICE_HOST` and `$ROOK_API_SERVICE_PORT` environment variables were not set up, so rookctl didn't work.  When I manually set them, rookctl worked.\r\n\r\n```\r\n% kubectl -n rook get services\r\nNAME       CLUSTER-IP   EXTERNAL-IP   PORT(S)    AGE\r\nrook-api   None         <none>        8124/TCP   1m\r\n% kubectl -n rook get pods -o wide | grep rook-api\r\nrook-api-388455989-b0g1k          1/1       Running   0          1m        172.17.8.103   172.17.8.103\r\n% kubectl -n rook exec -it rook-tools /bin/bash\r\nroot@rook-tools:/# rookctl block list                                                                                                                  \r\n$ROOK_API_SERVICE_HOST or $ROOK_API_SERVICE_PORT are not set. Check if the rook-api service is running.\r\nfailed to get block images: Get http:///image: http: no Host in request URL\r\nroot@rook-tools:/# export ROOK_API_SERVICE_PORT=8124\r\nroot@rook-tools:/# export ROOK_API_SERVICE_HOST=172.17.8.103\r\nroot@rook-tools:/# rookctl block list\r\nNAME                                       POOL          SIZE        DEVICE    MOUNT\r\npvc-9d695ec1-d477-11e7-80c5-001c4200cea2   replicapool   20.00 GiB   rbd       \r\npvc-9eef32a1-d477-11e7-80c5-001c4200cea2   replicapool   20.00 GiB   rbd       \r\nroot@rook-tools:/# \r\n```",
